<!-- BOUNDARY -->
What Was Sony Thinking?
Sony's new PSP Go is an update to the venerable PSP handheld gaming device. No doubt that it's a small sexy looking device but after giving it some thought I can't think of a single reason someone should get it.<br /><br />Aside from super sexy aesthetics what really differentiates the PSP Go from it's main competition (the Nintendo DS) is that it's an all digital device.  What does that mean?  Well, you no longer go to a physical store to buy games for the PSP Go because it doesn't have a slot for UMD games.  Like the iPhone it has an online store where you purchase and download all your games.  You'll be able to find PSP Mini games (smaller games that you'd find on the iPhone) as well as regular PSP games such as Gran Turismo.  Pretty cool huh?<br /><br />But think about this.  With a downloaded game, you can't share it with a friend without giving them your system.  Also you loose the ability to sell the game after you've finished it or realized that you actually hate the game and want to get back some of the cash you just wasted on it. So the only real benefit of an all digital system is that you get instant gratification.  See a game on the store you just have to play, pay, download and play.  That would be pretty cool except Sony botched up wireless service for the PSP Go.<br /><br />First off the PSP Go uses an old standard for wireless connectivity, 802.11b instead of the more recent and much faster g and n.  Why create a device that can only function wirelessly then use an outdated, slow standard?  But it doesn't end there.  Sony also designed the PSP Go so that if you are downloading a game and you loose the network connection for some reason (which tends to happen a lot more on the outdated b standard), the next time you connect the system doesn't pick up form where it left off but instead starts downloading all over again.  Insane!  It's not uncommon to hear reports of three hours download times for a single game.  Ouch!  And it's all because of the Sony is using older wi-fi technology.<br /><br />Why did Sony choose to make getting games such a pain in the neck?  Shouldn't this, the big selling point of the device, be quick, simple and painless?  I'd rather spend the three hours driving to a store, buying a game, getting home and playing it than just sitting around waiting for a download.  Oh did, I forget to mention that when the PSP Go is downloading you can't do anything else with the device?<br /><br />Aside from core functionality problems, there are other concerns.  Sony created a new proprietary connection cable for the PSP Go so all you previous PSP owners can't use any of the cables, or devices you have for the original system.  Controls are cramped and the system in uncomfortable to hold.  And of course to enjoy all the agony that the PSP Go offers you have to pay $250.  That's just $50 less than a PS3!  A Nintendo DSi is $170.  An iPod Touch is $199.  Why pay $250 when you can buy a PSP 3000 for $170 and it will do all the PSP Go does and more (like play UMD games and movies).<br /><br />It seems to me that the PSP Go will only appeal to blinded fan boys and gadget freaks.  Who else would want to deal with all the pain of ownership?
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
No significant new features; previous PSP models are more capable
Bottom line: Spend your money on a PSP-2000 or PSP-3000 plus a 8 or 16 GB memory stick (or just stick with your current PSP if you already have one). Aside from Bluetooth connectivity, the previous PSP models do everything the Go does, plus give you the option of playing UMD games and movies, plus work with the standard Mini USB transfer cable that you probably already have.<br /><br />Sony has put out some misleading advertising suggesting that downloading digital games from the PSN Store is a new feature unique to the Go, but every regular PSP can already do this. I really don't think this can be overstated: Every PSP can get online and download games in exactly the same way the Go can, and has been able to do so for a long time already. The Go does not even speed up transfers or allow downloads to run in the background. The functionality is exactly the same.<br /><br />(Note that while every piece of digital content playable on a PSP Go is also playable on the older PSP models, there are some UMD games that are not yet available on the PSN Store, and may never be. PSP Go owners are simply locked out of playing these games at all, in any form.)<br /><br />The PSP is a very impressive handheld system with a ton of great games already out, and many more promising games on the horizon. Sony's renewed focus on online content means that there has never been a better time to enter the PSP scene. Unfortunately, the Go is a botched release that is inferior to the previous PSP models in nearly every way.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Mission.... fail
I got the chance to play around with this thing without purchasing it, and I am glad I did not spend the $ 250. I am not quite sure what Sony was thinking when releasing this thing, but it was certainly not the customer who they had in mind. The Sony PSP was a great idea. The PSP go adds nothing new, yet gets rid of many of those things that made the PSP great. Here's what's new for the PSP GO:<br /><br />The good (new features)<br />1) Compact slider design (mind it does not come with a touch screen, which means it is unusable unless you slide it out)<br />2) 14GB of internal memory<br />3) Bluetooth<br />The bad<br />1) No support for UMD games and movies you may own. In other words, buy all your games again. You must now purchase all games from Sony for FULL retail price. Even those you already own.<br />2) No support for current PSP accessories. Wouldn't it be too nice to connect to the PC with a regular USB cable, as the PSP did? Sony thought so, inventing yet another proprietary cable.<br />3) New proprietary AC adapter. As if you did not have enough of them already.<br />4) Supports downloaded content ONLY. Yet, for some reason supports only the slow and ancient wireless-B standard. (and cannot do anything while downloading)<br />5) Screen has same resolution as the PSP and is smaller. <br />6) The regular PSP lets you change the battery, so you can replace it or carry a spare for long trips. As a new feature, the PSP Go has a non-replaceable battery, which conveniently turns it into a $ 250 paper weight in about 2-3 years.<br />7) Replaces the proprietary Memory Stick Duo with the even more obscure (and expensive) Memory Stuck Micro M2. <br /><br />All in all, why did Sony bring upon us this atrocity of a gaming system? You get much less for much more. You will pay arm and leg for downloadable games that will likely die when your PSPGo dies, so you can start over another time. Considering this thing works only with stuff directly from Sony, they should be giving it away for free or at a much lower price and make their money on digital downloads. Just buy the good old PSP 3000, which does EVERYTHING the PSP Go does (including playing downloaded content, except bluetooth), does many more things the PSP Go does not do (play UMD's, work with accessories, allow you to replace the battery, play custom content on the memory stick). Taking into consideration that the PSP Go uses pretty much the same hardware as the PSP 3000 (same processor, same wireless adapter), getting the Go for $ 100 more makes no sense at all.<br /><br /><br />
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
This product only has one demographic, and it's very narrow.  Garbage for everyone else.
The physical product itself is probably a two or three star rating.  I'm rating the entire package: the physical unit itself, Sony's (mis)handling of new products, how it compares to other similar devices (I left the DSi out to keep the focus on the PSP) and its impact on the future (small segment on this).  After play-testing one title from each genre on it, I can say this is a complete waste of Sony's development resources and consumers hard-earned cash.  I cannot in good conscience recommend it to anyone.  A little Googling will allow people to find great deals on the 2000 and 3000 models, which have many more features than this unit and are much more affordable.  Recently, I purchased a new 3000 model for around $[...] with Ratchet and Clank.  Even here on Amazon, the other models are $[...] less expensive.<br /><br />Compared to the older models, let me list the positives:<br /><br />-Sliding screen<br />-Lightweight<br />-DualShock 3 Support for home use  <br /><br />By shooting down comparisons to the older units and other similar devices, everyone suckered into buying this are trying to defend their ridiculously overpriced purchase.  Unfortunately for them, most of the world that uses these devices don't live in a vacuum.  As critical consumers, we must compare this unit to older ones or other all-in-one media devices.  If Sony wants to try and play with the big boys (Apple, etc.), then they need to take the heat.  <br /><br />Here are the things I do not like about the system:<br /><br />For current PSP owners:<br /><br />-Currently, no custom firmware.  As of today, even the 3000 model can run some functions of custom firmware, but only up to an extent.<br />-All new accessories that can't be carried over from the older models.<br />-New card slot, which makes the old cards useless.<br />-In the US, there is no UMD trading program.  At the last minute, Sony shot this idea down.  At least, international customers got something, but it was still far from Sony's initial boasts.   <br /><br />Current PSP owners have no reason to 'upgrade.'  The price is too expensive to own a Go and another model.  If the unit was around $[...], then I would reconsider that stance.<br /><br />Negatives for everyone (including current PSP owners):<br /><br />-16 GB is not enough space to hold a lot of games, especially, the more popular titles.  <br />-Digital-only delivery service, which essentially creates rental licenses.<br />-The controls and playing games is more uncomfortable than ever.<br />-Without heavy-duty eyestrain, the smaller screen makes RPGs and racing games unplayable.<br />-Users must convert all videos to Sony's format, which was a problem on the older units.<br />-Without Media Go, the device cannot properly function with a PC.  I guess if people can live with garbage like Itunes, then this isn't a big deal.<br />-Same battery life as the previous model.<br />-WiFi is still too slow to be useful.<br />-BlueTooth is a novelty and not really useful.  On a specific site, an entire forum thread was posted about how useless the feature is for tethering to a cellphone.    <br />-No background downloads for games.<br />-Proprietary USB cable.  A lot of companies do this.  On the older PSP units, I was happy to plug in generic cables into them.  Now, people will have another device with its own cable.  ANNOYING. <br />***The slider could break.  I've never broken one, but I know a lot of clumsy people.<br /><br />Things that should have been added for the exorbitant price:<br /><br />-Dual analog nubs.  The right one would emulate the buttons.  This issue has been addressed by the custom mod community, which makes the lack of one completely unacceptable.<br />-WiFi 'G' or 'N': the WiFi is just too slow by today's standards. <br />-Touchscreen.  If Sony wanted to compete against other all-in-one products (which is their strategy, even though, it's half-heartedly executed), then this should have been a no brainer.  <br />-A UMD slot with the ability to digitally rip games in an encrypted format to the memory stick, just like, the XBOX 360 installing feature for its system.  <br />***The D-Pad could use a makeover.  I can't complain about this much because the design is Sony's signature.  Unfortunately, the design makes fighting games almost unplayable and plenty of sore thumbs.<br /><br />For this system, only one demographic exists: people who don't already own a PSP, were curiously interested in one before, don't care to actually own games and will not buy anything that is larger than a certain size (even though DSi's are still larger than this but nobody complains about those).  That's it.<br /><br />Sony wanted to create an all-in-one multimedia device that competes with Apple and other similar products.  Unfortunately, it does not have a touchscreen, which makes it fall way behind similar units.  There is no keypad, so internet use is still cumbersome.  The browser is still terrible.  Also, why do people need every device to do everything?  How many more of these devices can clutter our lives?  Sony should have actually increased the PSP's functionality to better play games, instead of, trying to compete with superior devices in the all-in-one market segment.<br /><br />Honestly, I can't recommend this product to anyone.  The last three or four years, Sony has had a terrible run.  They are scrambling to re-capture their lost customer base, but their efforts are placed in all the wrong areas.  Their PR department needs a huge overhaul.  Since the inception of the PS3, Sony canceling the UMD-trading program was the last decision in a long line of poor PR moves.  From the top down, I think the company itself needs GOOD fresh ideas.<br /><br />On a grander scale, Sony's success with this product can only lead to one thing: gradual degradation of game ownership rights, which have been withering away for years.  For those that feel this is inevitable, I feel sad for you all.  Why should we pay companies the same money to give up rights we had before?  What benefit do we receive?  None.  Next time, before purchasing a product like this, please think hard about it.  You are all buying into a "way-of-life" and not just a product.  <br /><br />Thus, I am giving this product and company a one-star rating.  I would give it no stars, but that's not possible.
      
