Uncomfortable; mediocre sound
My main headphones are Sennheiser HD-595's, but I started a job in an office where open headphones aren't acceptable due to the amount of noise they bleed into the room.  I needed to buy a pair of closed headphones, and decided to stick with Sennheiser since I was so happy with my 595's.<br /><br />I was going to buy the HD-280's until I read the reviews for the HD-202's and saw how incredibly positive they were for a pair of $25 headphones.  So I bought them.<br /><br />They arrived today and the first thing I noticed when I put them on was how incredibly tight they were.  I hoped that I was just so used to my 595's being exceptionally comfortable, and that I would get used to it after a few hours.  So I plugged them in and started listening.<br /><br />The sound is not bad, especially for such cheap head phones.  But it definitely isn't great either -- nowhere near what most people here are claiming.  And Sennheiser has made up for the lower sound quality by severely boosting the bass.  The result is a very boomy sound similar to what you get from Sony.  While some people like this sound, it's extremely unnatural, and in my opinion does not "fix" the lack of quality at other frequencies.<br /><br />After a few hours of listening and adjusting to the fit as well as the sound, I still found them incredibly uncomfortable.  They pinched my ears tightly against my glasses and I eventually got a headache.  I have tried supra-aural headphones before without the sort of discomfort I experienced while wearing these.  I never adjusted to the bass either.<br /><br />I'm returning them and buying a pair of HD-280's.
      
