<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Another naysayer
Sales people in large appliance stores invariably represent Bose equipment as the best, "if you can afford it."  And among computer speaker systems, they say Companion 5 is the one.  Well, at $399, most of us need more than brand recognition and manufacturer hype--the sales person's stock and trade.    We want to know what C5 owners think.  Was the money worth it?  <br /><br />There are plenty of rave reviews on Amazon.  Five star ratings and comments on how much people love their Companion 5's, how superior these are to the competition, and how good music sounds through them.  There are some nay sayers, of course, there always are.  But these are said to be the usual Bose bashers, people who hesitate because of costs, high-end snobs (Bose is not really high-end), or people who can't or simply refuse to appreciate  a qualitative difference.<br /><br />I confess.  I bit on this slim evidence, bought the Companion 5 system, brought it home and began listening.  <br />I was immediately disappointed.  But then I expected to be after decades of hearing music through a high end stereo system.  It would be ridiculous to expect a $399 system to match well in that way.  Still, shouldn't the C5 perform better than this?  <br /><br />I went back and took a closer look at those negative reviews at Amazon.  "Thin, tinny.  Like listening through a phone line."  That was exactly how it sounded to me.  "The highs are extremely sharp, and hurt my ears."   "Strident, blaring." Yes, and because of this I can't take it for more than a few minutes at a time.  "The bass was too powerful" "muddy."  To me, the bass is a thump, thump, thump, and does overwhelm the vocals on some songs.  <br /><br />Now these are puzzling experiences since many reviewers were astonished by the musicality of their own speakers.  Different ears, different expectations, different computers, different music, different music source...?  <br /><br />Back to the store for another speaker system for a comparison.  Now I was able to switch back and forth between a Logitech Z2300 a 2:1 system.  For me at least, the Logitech, which sold at one third the price,  was far superior for listening to my I-tunes music.  It is hard to put musical experiences into words but it seemed to me that the music was warmer, more integrated--not so mechanical and partitioned.  I could hear  distinctive voice qualities from the vocalists.  If I were unfamiliar with the music, I couldn't have reliably identified singers through the Bose speakers.  And there was separation in the bass.  I could hear some detail, not just a murky thump, thump, etc.<br /><br />I called my wife in for a blind test.  She could care less about such things but agreed reluctantly while making it clear that she is against buying ANY new speaker equipment.  LIke me, she heard the differences immediately as I sneakily switched back and forth between the two systems.  She was put-off completely by the Bose system.  This was true for a wide range of music including folk, classical, rock, big band.  It was always the same.<br /><br />So, the question is, how can the Bose system sound so bad for some of us, and so good for others?   Does it really matter?  Those happy with their C5s will continue to be happy.  Others, like me, will return them to the store.  Those about to make a purchase can only listen and draw their own conclusions.    <br /><br /><br /><br />     <br /><br />                        <br /><br />
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Very Disappointed
I  just opened my new Soundsticks II system and am so very disappointed. They sound great with deep bass-intense music, like old R&B, but sound terrible for any music with significant sound in the higher end of frequency spectrum (nearly every pop & rock song). Music with a lot of sound in midrange and higher frequencies sounds very tinny - really just terrible. I will probably return them. Such a bummer, because they do look VERY cool.<br /><br />The instructions make it clear that the sound from these speakers is highly directional, so I've tried adjusting the position several times. This is not a positional issue. This is not an equalizer issue. The satellite speakers simply have a very harsh sound in the high frequency range. Almost like they are distorting. I cannot recommend these speakers to anyone.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Poor quality, poor support
This is a bike of very poor quality. To begin with, the bike was received with a pierced tire tube and incorrect seatpost size (the seatpost included was too wide to fit in the hole - this was confirmed by a bike shop). When I contacted Kent Bicycles for support, I received yet another incorrectly-sized seatpost, despite my specific instructions. Eventually, the bike shop had to order the seatpost at a cost of $20. Very quickly, the front gears broke and somehow bent, making the lowest gear unavailable for use. Eventually, once other components started breaking, I contact amazon.com for a replacement, and lo and behold, the incorrect size seatpost was included. Does Kent Bicycles send out this same incorrect seatpost for all Denali bikes?<br /><br />Bottom Line: Stay far far away from this product, and if you absolutely have to have it, buy it in-store, pre-assembled at Walmart.
      
