<!-- BOUNDARY -->
If you have Vista, I do NOT recommend getting this scanner!
I've been using a Canon CanoScan N650U since about Sept/Oct of 2000 for all of my scanning and it's always performed beautifully: however, in it's old age and in preparation for going to that great scanner heaven in the sky it's started leaving a faded stripe down all the images that I scan, from color photos to black and white sketches...it was time for a new scanner.<br /><br />I researched the Canon 8800F quite a bit and had my mind set on it when I went to buy a new scanner at B&H Photo in Manhattan, but I changed my mind while talking to the sales person.  He said that the HP G4050 and the 8800F were comparable (the HP being about $40 cheaper) - and both boxes claimed to be Vista Certified.  The reason that I went with the G4050 came down to one thing: it can scan 4x5 transparencies (negatives) which is extremely important to me as I photograph with a 4x5 view camera.  Also, due to the fact that it has a larger transparency/negative scanning area you can scan roughly twice the amount of slides or 35mm negatives at a time as you can with the 8800F.  I took my new scanner in hand and hopped on the A train as I headed back to Brooklyn, anxious to finally scan some old negatives that I'd never even had a chance to print...but I never got that chance.  <br /><br />As other reviewers have noted, the G4050 is a very large scanner - long, wide, thick.  That really didn't bother me even though I'm used to the very slim profile of my CanoScan N650U, but what did bother me immediately was this...<br /><br />When I opened up the instructions to get the scanner set to go, there was this discouraging note on an insert that had been printed in 9 languages - it read: "The HP Photosmart Software for HP Scanjet Scanners Windows Vista CD supports Windows Vista.  With Windows Vista, some features may not be available."  So, I just bought a brand new scanner, whose box claims to be Vista Certified, and now there's a note basically explaining that actually, not everything's going to work.  Like buying a new car and finding out that oh, the steering wheel doesn't quite work.  <br /><br />I downloaded the software anyway, wanting desperately to be one of the people who say "there are a lot of negative reviews, but this sucker is beautiful!" but my chance did not come.  All the software did was produce errors and have Vista try to find "a solution" online: it found nothing.  I had had my fill of the G4050.  I'm sure that if I had downloaded this and that, and called 27 different HP customer service reps that it would have finally "worked" but it's just not worth the effort.  I love HP printers, but this HP scanner is back at B&H.  And my brand new Canon 8800F is on the way.  <br />
      
